  "local_port": 50580,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "I'm a rookie. How should I start preparing for getting selected in GSoC 17?",
  "response": "Participating in [Google Summer of Code (GSoC)](https://summerofcode.withgoogle.com/) is a fantastic way to gain experience in open-source development, work with mentors, and contribute to meaningful projects. As a rookie, the process might seem daunting, but with systematic preparation, you can enhance your chances of being selected. Here's a comprehensive guide to help you get started:\n\n### 1. **Understand What GSoC Is**\n\n- **What It Is:** GSoC is an annual program sponsored by Google that offers stipends to university students for working on open-source projects during the summer.\n- **Objectives:** The main goals are to introduce students to open-source software development and to provide projects that organizations want to accomplish.\n\n### 2. **Research and Select a Participating Organization**\n\n- **Explore Organizations:** Visit the [list of participating organizations](https://summerofcode.withgoogle.com/archive/) from previous years to identify those that align with your interests and skills.\n- **Understand Their Projects:** Review the organizations' proposed projects to determine where you can contribute effectively.\n- **Community Engagement:** Join mailing lists, forums, or chat channels (like Slack or IRC) of these organizations to get a feel for their community and ongoing work.\n\n### 3. **Pick a Project Aligned with Your Skills and Interests**\n\n- **Assess Your Skills:** Honestly evaluate your current skills and identify areas you'd like to develop.\n- **Match Projects:** Choose projects that not only interest you but also match your skill set or the skills you aim to develop.\n- **Expand Your Horizons:** If you\u2019re eager to learn something new, select a project that challenges you while still being achievable.\n\n### 4. **Start Contributing Early**\n\n- **Familiarize with the Codebase:** Clone repositories, read documentation, and understand the project's architecture.\n- **Engage with the Community:** Start participating in discussions, asking questions, and offering help where possible.\n- **Complete Starter Tasks:** Many organizations have beginner-friendly issues labeled as \"good first issue\" or \"starter tasks.\" Completing these shows initiative and capability.\n- **Commit Regularly:** Make consistent contributions to demonstrate your commitment and ability to work within the project's workflow.\n\n### 5. **Improve Your Technical Skills**\n\n- **Learn the Required Technologies:** Identify the programming languages, frameworks, and tools used by your chosen organization and project. Utilize online resources like [freeCodeCamp](https://www.freecodecamp.org/), [Codecademy](https://www.codecademy.com/), or [Coursera](https://www.coursera.org/) to build proficiency.\n- **Build Relevant Projects:** Create small projects or contribute to other open-source projects to strengthen your understanding and showcase your skills.\n\n### 6. **Connect with Potential Mentors**\n\n- **Reach Out:** Introduce yourself to potential mentors by expressing interest, sharing your background, and asking insightful questions about the project.\n- **Seek Feedback:** Request feedback on your contributions or draft proposals to understand what organizations are looking for.\n- **Build Relationships:** Establishing a rapport with mentors can provide guidance, support, and advocacy during the selection process.\n\n### 7. **Prepare a Strong Proposal**\n\n- **Follow Guidelines:** Carefully read the [GSoC proposal guidelines](https://developers.google.com/open-source/gsoc/help/proposing) provided by Google and the organization.\n- **Clear Structure:** Include sections like project summary, objectives, technical approach, timeline, and your background.\n- **Detail Your Contribution:** Clearly outline what you plan to achieve, how you'll go about it, and how it benefits the project.\n- **Set Realistic Goals:** Ensure that your proposed timeline is achievable within the program's duration.\n- **Proofread:** Check for clarity, coherence, and absence of errors. A well-written proposal reflects professionalism.\n\n### 8. **Review Past Successful Proposals**\n\n- **Study Examples:** Read examples of past successful proposals to understand what worked well.\n- **Identify Best Practices:** Note the structure, level of detail, and tone used in these proposals to emulate in your writing.\n\n### 9. **Demonstrate Commitment and Consistency**\n\n- **Show Dedication:** Consistent contributions over time indicate reliability and genuine interest.\n- **Be Active:** Maintain regular communication with mentors and the community, showcasing your enthusiasm and commitment to the project.\n\n### 10. **Prepare for the Application Timeline**\n\n- **Mark Important Dates:** Keep track of key deadlines for application submission, proposal writing, and any pre-program activities.\n- **Plan Ahead:** Allocate sufficient time for research, drafting, revisions, and feedback before submission.\n\n### 11. **Seek Feedback and Iterate**\n\n- **Peer Reviews:** Have mentors, peers, or members of the open-source community review your proposal and provide constructive feedback.\n- **Iterate:** Incorporate the feedback to refine and improve your proposal before final submission.\n\n### 12. **Stay Updated and Flexible**\n\n- **Monitor Updates:** Keep an eye on announcements from GSoC and your chosen organization for any changes or additional requirements.\n- **Adapt as Needed:** Be prepared to adjust your proposal based on feedback or evolving project needs.\n\n### Additional Tips:\n\n- **Documentation is Key:** Properly document your work and contributions. Good documentation is a valuable asset in open-source projects.\n- **Networking:** Attend relevant webinars, workshops, or meetups to expand your network within the open-source community.\n- **Stay Persistent:** Rejections can happen, especially the first time. Use it as a learning experience to improve for the next cycle.\n\n### Useful Resources:\n\n- [GSoC Official Website](https://summerofcode.withgoogle.com/)\n- [GSoC FAQs](https://developers.google.com/open-source/gsoc/faqs)\n- [Open Source Guides](https://opensource.guide/)\n- [Free Programming Resources](https://github.com/EbookFoundation/free-programming-books)\n\nBy following these steps diligently and showcasing your passion for open-source development, you'll significantly improve your chances of being selected for GSoC. Remember, persistence and genuine contribution to the community are key. Good luck!",
